post_text:
You can still drop off school budget vote/Board of Education election ballots at Poland Central School until 5 p.m. today, Tuesday, June 9. The ballot box is under the bus canopy at the school.

Also, Gov. Andrew Cuomo on Sunday, June 7, signed an executive order extending the deadline for school districts to receive absentee ballots in the mail for the annual school budget vote and Board of Education election to Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

After 5 p.m. today, Tuesday, June 9, the ballot box must be removed and only ballots received in the mail can be accepted.

All ballots will remain unopened until 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 16, when school budget vote and Board of Education election results can be counted.

Gov. Andrew Cuomo issued Executive Order No. 202.26 on Friday, May 1, 2020, making several changes to the 2020 school board election and budget vote.

Please note the process and timeline for board elections:

School board candidates are not required to obtain nominating petition signatures, but must meet all other all other aspects of the nominating petition including applicable residency and age. To inquire about how to self-nominate for board elections, please contact Mrs. Wellington, District Clerk, at 315-826-0203.

The deadline to file is MONDAY, May 11, 2020.

Childcare placement is available to personnel who provide essential services, supplies, or support during this unprecedented time.

For a full list of personnel who may qualify, please visit the PCS website @ www.polandcsd.org and view the post in the Announcements section.

Additionally, a person deemed an essential employee may contact the Oneida-Herkimer-Madison Child Care Resource Center at 315-223-7850 extension 222 or by email using the address earlycareandlearning@cornell.edu for information on childcare placement.

The Child Care Resource Center will continue to evaluate and adjust plans in order to meet the childcare needs of essential personnel.

Thank you to all essential personnel who continue to protect and support our community.

We wish all members of our school community good health.

post_text:
You still have through this Friday to bring in plastic film for a recycling competition among kindergarten through fifth grade!

Poland Kids Against Pollution, Poverty and Prejudice club members have been busy weighing recycled plastic film this week!

Did you know that plastic film such as grocery bags can't be recycled through curbside recycling programs and shouldn't be thrown in the garbage?

Instead, bring in the plastic film this week in bins in the hallway near the elementary entrance to the school library. The winning class among kindergarten to fifth grade will win reusable water bottles and reusable bags.

All plastic must be clean, dry and free of food residue.

The following are examples of plastic film that can be brought in: grocery bags, bread bags, case overwrap, dry cleaning bags, newspaper sleeves, ice bags, wood pellet bags, Ziploc and other re-closable bags, produce bags, bubble wrap, salt bags and cereal bags.

Also check back next week for the results and a story about the KAP club's efforts!

You still have through this Friday to bring in plastic film for a recycling competition among kindergarten through fifth grade!

Poland Kids Against Pollution, Poverty and Prejudice club members have been busy weighing recycled plastic film this week!

Did you know that plastic film such as grocery bags can't be recycled through curbside recycling programs and shouldn't be thrown in the garbage?

Instead, bring in the plastic film this week in bins in the hallway near the elementary entrance to the school library. The winning class among kindergarten to fifth grade will win reusable water bottles and reusable bags.

All plastic must be clean, dry and free of food residue.

The following are examples of plastic film that can be brought in: grocery bags, bread bags, case overwrap, dry cleaning bags, newspaper sleeves, ice bags, wood pellet bags, Ziploc and other re-closable bags, produce bags, bubble wrap, salt bags and cereal bags.

Also check back next week for the results and a story about the KAP club's efforts!

INVITE TO POLAND ALUMNI:

The Poland Alumni Association is planning the next alumni dinner for Sunday, Aug. 18, 2019, at the Miner‚Äôs Table in Middleville, NY at 2 p.m. The following classes will be recognized this year: 1944, 1949, 1954, 1959, 1964, 1969, 1974, 1979, 1984, 1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009.

All Poland Alumni are welcome to attend, and all input is welcome. To receive your invitation, please send your address to Jeanette (Beaudin) Burns by email - jeanette_13324@hotmail.com, by Facebook to - Jeanette Burns, or by mail to - Jeanette Burns, 372 Christman Road, Cold Brook, NY 13324.

We hope to see you on Sunday, Aug. 18, 2019!
